<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-04-20T12:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-04-20T12:36:00-05:00" n="1075" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1075">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.113/447.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Consul at
                                    Guadalajara</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Guadalajara</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-20T11:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">April 20, 1912—11 a.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                                <lb/> (Received April 21, 1912—11.30 a.m.)</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>State and War Departments’ promptness in shipping arms almost nullified
                            by the failure Minister for Foreign Affairs to send permits to admit
                            them. Am still uninformed.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Magill.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>